# Queriva — Test Quality Rules

These rules define what a "good test" means for Queriva. Every test written
by Cursor must satisfy all applicable rules before an issue is considered done.

---

## SECTION A — Universal Test Rules (all languages)

### A1 — Tests are the specification
A test must read like a specification of behaviour, not a description of
implementation. If the test name requires knowing how the code works internally
to understand it, rename it.

```java
// BAD — describes implementation
@Test void testChunkServiceSlidingWindow() { ... }

// GOOD — describes behaviour
@Test void should_produce_overlapping_chunks_when_body_exceeds_chunk_size() { ... }
```

### A2 — One assertion group per test
Each test verifies one behaviour. Multiple `assert` calls are fine if they
all verify the same outcome. If a test needs to check two different behaviours,
write two tests.

```java
// BAD — two separate behaviours in one test
@Test void testIngest() {
    IngestResponse r = service.ingest(request);
    assertEquals(3, r.ingested());       // behaviour 1: count
    assertNull(r.errors());              // behaviour 2: no errors
    verify(qdrantClient, times(1))...;   // behaviour 3: qdrant called
}

// GOOD — split
@Test void should_report_correct_ingested_count() { ... }
@Test void should_report_no_errors_when_all_documents_succeed() { ... }
@Test void should_upsert_to_qdrant_once_per_chunk() { ... }
```

### A3 — Arrange / Act / Assert structure with blank lines
Every test body follows AAA with a blank line between sections.
No comments labelling the sections — the blank lines are sufficient.

```java
@Test
void should_return_top3_results_when_querying_seeded_collection() {
    String query = "floods in Dhaka";
    String collection = "news_radar";

    SearchResponse response = searchService.search(query, collection, 3, 0.60, "search", null);

    assertThat(response.results()).hasSize(3);
    assertThat(response.results().get(0).score()).isGreaterThan(0.60);
}
```

### A4 — No test depends on another test's state
Tests are independent. No `@TestMethodOrder`, no shared mutable state between
tests, no assumptions about execution order.

Each test must set up its own data and clean up after itself (or use
`@BeforeEach`/`@AfterEach`).

### A5 — No Thread.sleep or time.sleep in tests
Use `Awaitility` (Java) or `pytest-asyncio` (Python) for async assertions.
Sleeping is flaky by definition.

```java
// BAD
Thread.sleep(2000);
assertEquals("ok", response.status());

// GOOD
await().atMost(5, SECONDS).until(() -> health().status().equals("ok"));
```

### A6 — Test data is realistic, not minimal
Use data that resembles production. For Queriva: real news article titles,
real multilingual content (Bangla + English), realistic score values.

The fixture file `fixtures/news_radar_dhaka_floods.json` is the canonical
test corpus. All ingest and search tests use this fixture or a subset of it.

```java
// BAD
Document doc = new Document("id1", "title", "body", "src", "en", null, null, null);

// GOOD
Document doc = new Document(
    "cluster-001",
    "Buriganga river overflows, floods low-lying Dhaka areas",
    "Heavy monsoon rains caused the Buriganga river to overflow its banks...",
    "prothomalo.com", "bn", "2026-06-15T08:30:00Z", "national",
    "https://prothomalo.com/bangladesh/article-xyz"
);
```

### A7 — Edge cases are tested explicitly
For every method, test at least:
- Happy path (normal input, expected output)
- Empty input (empty string, empty list, zero)
- Boundary values (min_score=0.0, top_k=1, top_k=100)
- Invalid input (null, blank, wrong type)
- Failure path (service down, Qdrant unreachable)

### A8 — Test names follow a convention
```
Java:    should_[expected_outcome]_when_[condition]()
Python:  test_[unit]_[condition]_[expected_outcome]
Vitest:  it('should [expected outcome] when [condition]', ...)
```

### A9 — Coverage is a floor, not a target
Minimum coverage thresholds are enforced by CI but coverage percentage
is not the goal — meaningful coverage is.

| Package | Line coverage minimum |
|---|---|
| api (unit) | 80% |
| embed-sidecar | 90% |
| ingest-cli | 80% |
| ui (components + hooks) | 80% |

A 95% coverage score with trivial getter tests is worse than 80% coverage
with meaningful behaviour tests.

### A10 — Flaky tests are treated as bugs
A test that passes sometimes and fails sometimes is a bug in the test.
Open a GitHub issue immediately. Do not merge flaky tests. Do not
`@Disabled` without a linked issue.

